Press room

Press Releases

Press releases 2016

11 May 2016: Healthcare sector

   The Autorité de la concurrence issues an unfavourable opinion
   on the draft decree establishing a code of ethics for nurses.

   > Version française
   In brief

   Following a referral from the French Ministry of Health, the Autorité
   de la concurrence has issued major reservations regarding several
   provisions in the draft code of ethics for nurses, drawn up by the
   National Order of Nurses (Ordre national des infirmiers).

   The draft code of ethics frequently endorses the most restrictive
   provisions of the codes of ethics of other healthcare professions. In
   many cases these are provisions that the Autorité de la concurrence (or
   the Conseil before it) had already flagged in previous opinions. Given
   the increasing need for domestic care services as a result of the
   ageing of the population and the rise of outpatient treatment, the
   opportunity exists for self-employed nurses to develop their activity.
   The code of ethics for nurses is an innovation in the sector. However,
   rather than adhering faithfully to codes of the past, it should be
   tailored to the profession's realities and future, for the benefit of
   patients and professionals alike. The Autorité has, therefore, issued a
   series of recommendations that will facilitate the liberal exercise of
   nursing, while at the same time respecting the essential requirements
   of public healthcare.

   Competition should be encouraged

   Nurses constitute the largest sector of healthcare professionals in
   France (500,000 nurses according to data from the National Order of
   Nurses). More than 80% work in salaried positions while 16% are
   self-employed. Nevertheless, the percentage of self-employed nurses is
   likely to increase, given the increase in domestic care services and
   opportunities for higher earnings.

   As tariffs for all acts performed by nurses are set out in the
   profession's official convention, there is no competition on price. As
   a result, competition can only be exercised on the basis of other
   parameters. It is therefore important that the few existing competitive
   areas (the forms in which the profession is carried out) are maintained
   so that new entrants, such as newly qualified nurses, can stimulate
   competition and develop new healthcare offers for their patients.
   However, the draft decree submitted to the Autorité contains major
   competition restrictions which are not justified on public healthcare
   grounds.

   THE AUTORITE'S MAIN RECOMMENDATIONS
     * Removal of the reference to a decrease in fees

   The draft decree prohibits nurses from lowering their fees. However, as
   nurses are almost all bound by their Social Security convention, they
   do not have any tariff freedom. Consequently this prohibition can be
   removed as irrelevant.
     * Allow nurses to provide information on their speciality

   Nurses, like other healthcare professionals, are not allowed to
   advertise. They are only authorised to provide information on their
   name, practice address, practice details and opening hours, information
   which is predominantly provided via directories. By contrast, nurses
   may not provide information on their specialist qualifications. This
   information would, however, allow patients to optimise their choice.
   Indeed, it is one of the rare elements that allows nurses to
   differentiate themselves in a sector where prices, acts and
   establishment are completely restricted. The Autorité also recommends
   that nurses be allowed to provide information on their speciality.

   It is also calling for the formats authorised for the provision of
   information to be extended to include the internet, a channel that is
   essential in this day and age but which has not been identified in the
   authorised provisions.
     * Make opening secondary practices more flexible

   Opening a secondary practice (in addition to a main practice) can only
   be done within a very strict framework and requires the authorisation
   of the National Order of Nurses. However, the zoning set out in the
   Convention is sufficient to meet the aims of an effective distribution
   of professionals across French territory. The Autorité contends that
   the National Order of Nurses would not be legitimate, or sufficiently
   experienced and neutral, to be responsible for this. It therefore
   recommends that the current system of prior control is made more
   flexible through the introduction of a system requiring the simple
   declaration of the opening of any secondary practice to the competent
   regional council of the National Order of Nurses. This would encourage
   the establishment of secondary practices.
     * Limit the non-competition period after a replacement

   In order to avoid the poaching of patients, if a nurse has replaced a
   colleague for three months, be they "consecutive or otherwise", he/she
   may not set up in competition to the latter within the next two years.
   However, the description "consecutive or otherwise" is liable to extend
   the reference period for the calculation of the duration of
   replacements for an unlimited period. Therefore, the Autorité proposes
   that the description "consecutive or otherwise" be deleted, or
   restricted to a maximum period.
     * Allow the replacement of more than 2 nurses

   On the grounds of maintaining the quality of the staff who are
   employed, the draft code likewise envisages that a nurse cannot replace
   more than two nurses at the same time. However, it does not appear
   justified to proceed with an a priori ban on any replacement of more
   than two nurses. The Autorité would therefore suggest that the choice
   of the number of replacements is left to the discretion of each nurse,
   in respect of healthcare quality and safety regulations.
     * Make the establishment of a practice more flexible

   It is prohibited for nurses to establish a practice in the same
   building or in the immediate proximity of a practice where a colleague
   is operating, without obtaining their agreement, or the agreement of
   the departmental council of the National Order of Nurses. The Autorité
   considers that this provision is too restrictive. It recommends that
   the prohibition only extends to the establishment at the same address
   as another nurse's practice with which the newcomer has been linked by
   a contract for joint practice.
     * Increase the number of fellow workers per practice

   A nurse cannot work in joint practice with more than one other
   self-employed nurse. This provision is not necessary or proportionate
   to the aim of preventing the possible commercial drift of practices.
   The Autorité proposes that nurses should be able to work with several
   fellow workers.
     * Develop the salaried work-force

   Paying a salary to nurses in private practice, as well as student
   nurses, assistant nurses, childcare assistants and psychological
   support staff, is prohibited. The system governing the nursing
   profession therefore numbers among one of the most restrictive in the
   healthcare profession. The Autorité is of the opinion that this
   prohibition should be lifted. It believes that further thought should
   be given to how a salary arrangement could be put into place that would
   be compatible with the rules of the profession and, in particular, with
   its independence.

   > Consult the full text of Opinion 16-A-11 of 11 May 2016 on a draft
   decree on a code of ethics for nurses
   > Press contact: Aurore Giovannini / Tel.: +33 1 55 04 0 1 81 Email





